Cloud computing is the delivery of computing services over the Internet. Instead of owning and maintaining physical hardware, organizations can access resources such as servers, storage, and applications on demand.
Cloud services provide flexibility, scalability, and cost efficiency.

Why Use the Cloud?

Reduced hardware costs
Scalability based on demand
Access from anywhere with an Internet connection
Faster deployment of services
Simplified maintenance

Cloud Service Models:

Infrastructure as a Service (IaaS)
Provides virtualized computing resources such as servers, storage, and networking.

Examples:
Amazon EC2
Microsoft Azure Virtual Machines

Platform as a Service (PaaS)
Provides a platform for developing and deploying applications without managing underlying infrastructure.

Examples:
Google App Engine
Azure App Service

Software as a Service (SaaS)
Provides complete applications over the Internet.

Examples:

Gmail
Microsoft 365
Dropbox

Cloud Deployment Models

Public Cloud
Resources are owned and managed by a third-party provider and shared among customers.

Private Cloud
Cloud infrastructure dedicated to a single organization.

Hybrid Cloud
A combination of public and private cloud environments.

Cloud Security Considerations

Organizations must protect:

User accounts
Sensitive data
Cloud configurations
Access permissions

Common security controls include:

Multi-Factor Authentication (MFA)
Encryption
Access control policies
Continuous monitoring

Key Takeaways:
Cloud computing delivers IT resources over the Internet.
IaaS, PaaS, and SaaS are the main service models.
Public, private, and hybrid clouds are common deployment models.
Security remains a shared responsibility between the provider and the customer.
